06136nam a22008895i 9780812295184DE-B159720210526051534.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210526t20182019pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97808122951847 a10.9783/97808122951842doi  a(DE-B1597)502048  a(OCoLC)1046990216  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 4aPN2590.R35b.G876 2018 7aLIT0190002bisacsh04a792.0942/090312231 aGurnis, Musa, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aMixed Faith and Shared Feeling :bTheater in Post-Reformation London /cMusa Gurnis. 1aPhiladelphia : bUniversity of Pennsylvania Press, c[2018] 4cÂ©2019  a1 online resource (272 p.) :b5 illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tIntroduction -- tChapter 1. Mixed Faith -- tChapter 2. Shared Feeling -- tChapter 3. In Mixed Company: Collaboration in Commercial Theater -- tChapter 4. Making a Public Through A Game at Chess -- tChapter 5. Measure for Measure: Theatrical Cues and Confessional Codes -- tEpilogue: Pity in the Public Sphere -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex -- tAcknowledgments0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aMixed Faith and Shared Feeling explores the mutually generative relationship between post-Reformation religious life and London's commercial theaters. It explores the dynamic exchange between the imaginatively transformative capacities of shared theatrical experience, with the particular ideological baggage that individual playgoers bring into the theater. While early modern English drama was shaped by the polyvocal, confessional scene in which it was embedded, Musa Gurnis contends that theater does not simply reflect culture but shapes it. According to Gurnis, shared theatrical experience allowed mixed-faith audiences to vicariously occupy alternative emotional and cognitive perspectives across the confessional spectrum.In looking at individual plays, such as Thomas Middleton's A Game of Chess and Shakespeare's Measure for Measure, Gurnis shows how theatrical process can restructure playgoers' experiences of confessional material and interrupt dominant habits of religious thought. She refutes any assumption that audiences consisted of conforming Church of England Protestants by tracking the complex and changing religious lives of seventy known playgoers. Arguing against work that seeks to draw fixed lines of religious affiliation around individual playwrights or companies, she highlights the common practice of cross-confessional collaboration among playhouse colleagues. Mixed Faith and Shared Feeling demonstrates how post-Reformation representational practices actively reshaped the ways ideologically diverse Londoners accessed the mixture of religious life across the spectrum of beliefs.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mai 2021) 0aEnglish dramay17th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aEnglish dramayEarly modern and Elizabethan, 1500-1600xHistory andcriticism. 0aTheater and societyzGreat BritainxHistoryy16th century. 0aTheater and societyzGreat BritainxHistoryy17th century. 0aTheater audienceszGreat BritainxReligious aspectsxHistoryy16th century. 0aTheater audienceszGreat BritainxReligious aspectsxHistoryy16thcentury. 0aTheater audienceszGreat BritainxReligious aspectsxHistoryy17th century. 0aTheater audienceszGreat BritainxReligious aspectsxHistoryy17thcentury. 0aTheaterzGreat BritainxReligious aspectsxHistoryy16th century. 0aTheaterzGreat BritainxReligious aspectsxHistoryy17th century. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Renaissance.2bisacsh  aCultural Studies.  aLiterature.  aMedieval and Renaissance Studies.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2018 Englishz97831